channel.title: Mt Charlie Reserve FLORA, Riddells Creek
channel.description: Mt Charlie Flora & Fauna Reserve, not including Mt Teneriffe. Initial species list from a combination of Ian Lunt's surveys conducted after the 1983 bushfire (with name updates by Russell Best) and surveys by Riddells Creek Landcare members (a total of 230 species, natives and weeds).

item.title: Pultenaea humilis
item.dc:creator: david_francis
item.description: Not common in the Macedon Ranges

item.title: Drosera peltata subsp. auriculata, Pieris rapae rapae
item.dc:creator: david_francis
item.description: Cabbage White Butterfly trapped by Sundew

item.title: Olearia glandulosa
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Approaching the end of its flowering time.

item.title: Cassytha pubescens s.s.
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: New species record for Mt Charlie Reserve. Only the second plant I've seen in the area (the other at Mt Teneriffe).

item.title: Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh Albrecht & Knox (2010)
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Confirmed ID from seed etc. About two dozen plants over 10x10m. No other populations of this species are known in Riddells Creek.
item.category: id~Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh Albrecht & Knox (2010)

item.title: Prostanthera lasianthos var. lasianthos
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Note eggs in upper right corner of 2nd photo.

item.title: Xanthorrhoea australis
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Two plants flowering following a late burn (some time Autumn-Winter, not sure when).

item.title: Plantago debilis
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Sepals about 1.5mm long. Flower/fruit is much smaller than for P. varia. This plant found in a damper roadside, reconfirms the species for Riddells Creek as found by I. Lunt in 1984/5. First time I've seen it in Riddells Creek.

item.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. armeria
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: This plant about 1.2m tall, very long leaves and large flowers (relative to the other subsp. depicted nearby in observation 11370).

item.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. pilosifolium
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Recent burn has revealed numerous plants (we saw 25ish so possibly 100ish overall) spread over a narrow area with limits as detailed by the 3 plants depicted here.

item.title: Diptera spp., Hydrocotyle laxiflora
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Tiny flies over Stinking Pennywort.

item.title: Eucalyptus globulus subsp. bicostata
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: This subspecies is defined by fruit in 3s and fruit sessile (stalkless). Small copse of young trees - not aware of any other populations in Riddells Creek. Possibly be a weed but hard to tell.

item.title: Dispar compacta, Senecio linearifolius var. linearifolius
item.dc:creator: russell

item.title: Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh Albrecht & Knox (2010)
item.dc:creator: david_francis
item.category: id~Lobelia gibbosa sensu Walsh Albrecht & Knox (2010)

item.title: Olearia glandulosa
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Upright shrub, about 2.5m tall. Only one plant seen. Not formally recorded in Macedon Range since Ian Lunt's 1984 study. Probably locally very rare.

item.title: Wahlenbergia stricta subsp. stricta
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Showing campanulate (bell-shaped) flower tube.

item.title: Conium maculatum
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: A declared noxious weed.

item.title: Prunella vulgaris
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: In a swampy area.

item.title: Acacia pravissima
item.dc:creator: jamesbooth
item.description: I suspect the main plant was deliberately planted on the side of the track but there were seedlings that were obviously not planted.

item.title: Sambucus gaudichaudiana
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Not previously recorded in Riddells Creek. Growing on the edge of Charlies Creek.

item.title: Olearia rugosa subsp. rugosa
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Previously unknown here. Now subsp. rugosa.

item.title: Coprosma quadrifida
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: First record of this species for Riddells Creek.

item.title: Acacia mucronata subsp. longifolia
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Location approximate.

item.title: Pterostylis parviflora s.s.
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Green tip = P. parviflora s.s.. Look is very different to P. sp. aff. parviflora (Southern Victoria) plants nearby on Barrm Birrm & Pyrete. One plant seen. Reddening old flowers is more like P. sp. aff. parviflora (Southern Victoria). Photo David Francis.

item.title: 58 ids
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Short walk along Mt Charlie Rd from Mt Teneriffe Rd intersection. Location is where I stopped and turned back (at a large yellow Euc, covered in yellow lichen). This road has Mt Teneriffe on one side and Mt Charlie of the other, with creek running alongsi

item.title: 81 ids
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Walk with David Francis from Rowallan Scout Camp on Mt Kent Rd, over the top to the bare area and down to the Eatons Rd loop track. Location is near top of hill.

item.title: Platylobium obtusangulum
item.dc:creator: david_francis
item.description: Previously unrecorded in the Macedon Ranges

item.title: Banksia marginata
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Open, lanky shrubs, mostly to about 2m tall. The most common mid-level shrub in this part of the reserve.

item.title: Olearia rugosa subsp. rugosa
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: One small patch in a lovely spot among Banksia marginata, Correa reflexa var. reflexa (cream) and Grass Trees. Location approximate. Now subsp. rugosa.

item.title: Eucalyptus globulus subsp. bicostata
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Small population of young trees.

item.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. pilosifolium
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Just a few plants noticed in a dry, shaly area with larger than normal (for Mt Charlie Reserve) inter-tussock spaces.

item.title: 89 ids

item.description: Survey walking around the circular path/road accessed from Eatons Road. Location is iPhone GPS taken at start/finish point on Eatons Rd..
